<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">29729784</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2019</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>03</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2019</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>03</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1558-1977</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>32</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2018</Year><Month>Jun</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>Hematology/oncology clinics of North America</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Hematol Oncol Clin North Am</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Mindfulness-Based Interventions for Hematology and Oncology Patients with Pain.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>493</StartPage><EndPage>504</EndPage><MedlinePgn>493-504</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.hoc.2018.01.013</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0889-8588(18)30023-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Pain is a reality for approximately half of all of patients with cancer and can negatively affect patient cognitive and emotional states, resulting in "total pain." Total pain may not respond to pharmacologic interventions and may pave the way for the onset of suffering, where suffering is defined as physical pain accompanied by negative cognitive interpretations. Mindfulness-based interventions provide an alternate interpretive framework for both pain and suffering and may lessen a patient's experience of pain. Mindfulness-based interventions have the potential to alter a patient's relationship to pain, reducing pain catastrophizing, and enhancing patient reported overall well-being.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2018 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Hess</LastName><ForeName>Denise</ForeName><Initials>D</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Supportive Care Coa